THOUGHT

The observed crash is an AddressSanitizer stack-buffer-overflow at `program.c:13` inside `strcpy`. The local stack object `buf` is exactly 256 bytes, but the first command-line argument is about 600 bytes, so `strcpy(buf, argc[1])` copies all bytes plus the terminator past the end of `buf`. The second argument copy into `pbuf` is not the failing operation for the supplied command; a short first argument with the same second argument exits normally. There are also structural quality issues: `main` uses misleading parameter names (`argv` as count, `argc` as vector), does not validate argument count, omits required headers in gnu89 causing implicit declarations, and uses raw C string APIs/pointers.

ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:13` copies unbounded attacker-controlled input `argc[1]` into fixed-size stack array `char buf[256]` using `strcpy`. When the first argument length is >= 256, `strcpy` writes beyond `buf`'s 256-byte storage, corrupting the stack redzone and producing the ASan stack-buffer-overflow. The code has no length check or truncation policy before the copy.

LOCAL FIX: Replace the unbounded copy with an explicit bounds check or bounded copy, and validate argument count. Prefer rejecting too-long input rather than silent truncation:
```diff
+#include <stdio.h>
+#include <stdlib.h>
+#include <string.h>
+
-int main(int argv,char **argc) {
-       char *pbuf=malloc(strlen(argc[2])+1);
+int main(int argc, char **argv) {
+       if (argc < 3) {
+               fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s ARG1 ARG2\n", argv[0]);
+               return 2;
+       }
+       if (strlen(argv[1]) >= 256) {
+               fprintf(stderr, "ARG1 too long\n");
+               return 2;
+       }
+       char *pbuf = malloc(strlen(argv[2]) + 1);
+       if (!pbuf) return 1;
        char buf[256];

-       strcpy(buf,argc[1]);
-       for (;*pbuf++=*(argc[2]++););
+       strcpy(buf, argv[1]);
+       strcpy(pbuf, argv[2]);
        exit(1);
 }
```
If truncation is desired instead, use `snprintf(buf, sizeof buf, "%s", argv[1])` and check whether the return value exceeded the buffer.

GLOBAL FIX: Stop passing unbounded NUL-terminated strings into raw fixed-size buffers. Define APIs around `(pointer,length)`/bounded string views plus destination capacity, or dynamically allocate destination strings based on `strlen(input)+1` with checked allocation. Centralize safe copy helpers that always receive capacity and report overflow, compile with full warnings as errors (`-Wall -Wextra -Werror`, no `-Wno-implicit-function-declaration`), include proper headers, and keep sanitizers/FORTIFY in CI so unbounded APIs like `strcpy` cannot be introduced without review.
